frameDefinitions: This frame refers to a part of an organization that becomes separate from the main body.
Criteria exist that identify a particular Subset of a Group of things into members and non-members.
This frame involves a Creator making a duplicate, the Copy, of some Original entity.
A Term is the linguistic sign conventionally used by a Speaker to refer to a type of Entity.
The words in this frame describe situations in which a Perpetrator carries off and holds the Victim against his or her will by force. ''
This frame has to do with nouns denoting types of entities.

listRoleDefinitions: The offshoot or branch of the original body which differs from it in some important respect.
The time at which the <fen>Branch</fen> forms or thrives.
The place in which the <fen>Branch</fen> is locate or where it first forms.
A representation of the conditions upon which membership to a <fen>Subset</fen> of a <fen>Group</fen> is determined.
The members of a <fen>Group</fen> that fulfill particular <fen>Criteria</fen> to belong to a <fen>Subset</fen> of the <fen>Group</fen>.
The numerical representation of the size of the <fen>Subset</fen> relative to the size of the <fen>Group</fen>.
The <fen>Creator</fen> produces the <fen>Copy</fen> based on the <fen>Original</fen>.  It is normally expressed as an External Argument.
The <fen>Original</fen> is the entity which is copied. With verbs it is frequently expressed as an NP Object:
The <fen>Copy</fen> produced by the <fen>Creator</fen> is frequently not expressed. However, when <fen>Copy</fen> does occur, it is usually expressed as the External Argument of verbs:
The linguistic sign that is used for referring to a type of <fen>Entity</fen>.
The type of <fen>Entity</fen> that is conventionally referred to by a <fen>Term</fen>.
The <fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) who carries off and holds the <fen>Victim</fen> against his or her will.
The <fen>Victim</fen> is the person who is carried off and held against his/her will.
The entity which denotes a subtype of the more general <fen>Category</fen>.
The more general type that the target denotes a subtype of. This role is obligatory and should be labeled DNI when not present.
